    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-03-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-03-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="1042"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1042">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 211.52L89/2.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Minister of Spain</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-03-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 9, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 34.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to your request made to-day at the
                    Department for the arrest at New York of Tómas Loscesta and Lazareto Calvo,
                    charged in Spain with fraud, I have the honor to inclose copy of a telegram
                    which has been sent to the Attorney General asking that the United States
                    attorney at New York be instructed by telegraph to take the matter up with the
                    Spanish consul general and to assist him in securing the arrest of the accused
                    parties, in pursuance of article 13 of the extradition treaty between Spain and
                    the United States. I also transmit herewith copy of the form of preliminary
                    mandate.</p>
                <p>Accept, etc.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
